Then, let us now determine the effects of each offering price on the current price per share using the formula from step 3. Let us start with $77.00 offer price. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Ex-rights price}&=\dfrac{\text{(5.5 $\times$ \$77.00) + 77.00}}{\text{1 + 5.5}}\\[10pt]
&={\textbf{\$77.00}}
\end{aligned}$$ 

**There will be no change in the price per share because the ex-rights price is still $77.00.**

Next, let us compute the ex-rights price with $73.00 offer price. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Ex-rights price}&=\dfrac{\text{(5.5 $\times$ \$77.00) + 73.00}}{\text{1 + 5.5}}\\[10pt]
&={\textbf{\$76.38}}
\end{aligned}$$ 

**There will be a decrease in the price per share because the ex-rights price amounts to $76.38.**

Now, let us compute the ex-rights price with $65.00 offer price. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Ex-rights price}&=\dfrac{\text{(5.5 $\times$ \$77.00) + 65.00}}{\text{1 + 5.5}}\\[10pt]
&={\textbf{\$75.15}}
\end{aligned}$$ 

**There will still be a decrease in the price per share because the ex-rights price amounts to $75.15.**
